<section xml:id="sec-apps-of-diagonalisation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Applications of diagonalisation</title>

<p>
One of the useful things about diagonalisation is that it allows us to quickly compute large powers 
of matrices. If <m>A = PDP\inv</m>, then most of the <m>P</m> and <m>P\inv</m> terms will cancel: 
we have <m>A^2 = (PDP\inv)(PDP\inv) = PD(P\inv P)DP\inv = PD^2 P\inv</m>. Similarly, for any 
integer power <m>m \gt  0</m>, we have
<me>
A^m = PD^m P\inv
</me>.
Recall that if <m>D</m> is a diagonal matrix, the power <m>D^m</m> can be computed simply by 
taking the <m>m</m>th power of each diagonal entry. Then we just need to multiply it by <m>P</m> 
(on the left) and <m>P\inv</m> (on the right) to find <m>A^m</m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-power-using-diagl">
<statement>
<p>
Use diagonalisation to calculate <m>A^{1000}</m> where
<me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  0 \amp  2 \amp  1 \\ -2 \amp  4 \amp  1\\ -2 \amp  2 \amp  3
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
</p>
<p>
In <xref ref="ex-diagl"/>, we saw that <m>A = PDP\inv</m> is diagonalisable, with
<me>
P =
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  1 \amp  \frac{1}{2} \\ 1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\ 1 \amp  0 \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}
, \qquad D =
\begin{bmatrix}
  3 \amp  0 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  2 \amp  0\\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  2
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
Therefore
<me>
A^{1000} = PD^{1000}P\inv =
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  1 \amp  \frac{1}{2} \\ 1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\ 1 \amp  0 \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
  3^{1000} \amp  0 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  2^{1000} \amp  0\\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  2^{1000}
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  1 \amp  \frac{1}{2} \\ 1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\ 1 \amp  0 \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}
\inv
</me>.
This could be simplified further by evaluating the inverse and the matrix products.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

</section>